The union of set A and set B, denoted as A ∪ B, is the set of all elements that are in A, in B, or in both. In this case, A ∪ B = {2, 3, 5, 7}.

Now, we need to show that the resulting set {2, 3, 5, 7} is a superset of both set A and set B. A set C is a superset of a set D if every element of D is also an element of C.

For set A:
- 2 is in {2, 3, 5, 7}
- 3 is in {2, 3, 5, 7}
- 5 is in {2, 3, 5, 7}

For set B:
- 3 is in {2, 3, 5, 7}
- 5 is in {2, 3, 5, 7}
- 7 is in {2, 3, 5, 7}

Since every element of set A and set B is also an element of the resulting set {2, 3, 5, 7}, we can conclude that {2, 3, 5, 7} is a superset of both set A and set B.
